<TextWithNodes><Node id="0"/>Manufacturers will be forced to axe nearly 30,000 more jobs by the <Node id="67"/>end of September<Node id="83"/> as the downturn in the world economy piles further pressure on British firms, industry leaders warned <Node id="186"/>yesterday<Node id="195"/>.
<Node id="197"/>The <Node id="201"/>Confederation of British Industry<Node id="234"/> described the cuts as &quot;severe even by <Node id="273"/>UK<Node id="275"/> standards&quot; and said they would be spread across all regions, with the previously buoyant south-east the worst affected.<Node id="395"/>

<Node id="397"/>The <Node id="401"/>CBI<Node id="404"/>&apos;s latest quarterly regional snapshot shows the impact of the global downturn fanning out from <Node id="499"/>Britain<Node id="506"/>&apos;s manufacturing heartlands to hi-tech centres in the south-east, <Node id="572"/>Northern Ireland<Node id="588"/> and <Node id="593"/>Scotland<Node id="601"/>. Worryingly the pace of job losses is increasing.<Node id="651"/>

<Node id="653"/>&quot;The global slowdown is now hitting <Node id="689"/>UK<Node id="691"/> manufacturing hard, with firms in virtually all regions experiencing falling orders, output and employment with severe pressure on profit margins,&quot; said <Node id="845"/>Sudhir Junankar<Node id="860"/>, the <Node id="866"/>CBI<Node id="869"/>&apos;s associate director of economic analysis.<Node id="912"/>

<Node id="914"/>More than 8,000 jobs are under threat in <Node id="955"/>London<Node id="961"/> and the south-east, the largest lay-offs since the last recession. The <Node id="1033"/>east Midlands<Node id="1046"/> will shed 5,000 jobs and the north-west, 4,000.<Node id="1094"/>

<Node id="1096"/>&quot;Previously resilient regions are experiencing the pain as much as traditional manufacturing areas, as the downturn has affected new technology sectors,&quot; said <Node id="1255"/>Peter Gutmann<Node id="1268"/> of <Node id="1272"/>Business Strategies<Node id="1291"/>, which jointly published the survey.<Node id="1328"/>

<Node id="1330"/>Last week<Node id="1339"/>&apos;s surprise interest rate cut by the <Node id="1376"/>Bank of England<Node id="1391"/> was &quot;clearly justified&quot;, <Node id="1417"/>Mr Junankar<Node id="1428"/> said, adding more cuts might be needed to prop up the economy if consumer spending falters.<Node id="1520"/>

<Node id="1522"/>The <Node id="1526"/>CBI<Node id="1529"/> predicted worse times ahead for the manufacturing sector - severely hit by the high value of sterling - which is back in recession according to government figures published earlier <Node id="1711"/>this week<Node id="1720"/>.<Node id="1721"/>

<Node id="1723"/>Export orders, which have held up relatively well so far despite sterling&apos;s strength, are set to nosedive. The <Node id="1834"/>CBI<Node id="1837"/> survey shows that firms&apos; optimism about export prospects is falling at its fastest rate in almost three years as overseas markets contract.<Node id="1977"/>

<Node id="1979"/>&quot;International developments are making life very tough for manufacturers,&quot; said <Node id="2059"/>Mr Gutmann<Node id="2069"/>. &quot;The pound&apos;s persistent strength and weak global demand account for widespread falls in confidence.&quot;<Node id="2171"/>

<Node id="2173"/>Economists believe unemployment is likely to start rising in the coming months, denting consumer spending, which has so far insulated the <Node id="2311"/>UK<Node id="2313"/> from the worst of the world slowdown.<Node id="2351"/>

<Node id="2353"/>&quot;The lay-offs are likely to come in the <Node id="2393"/>third quarter<Node id="2406"/> and will hit consumer confidence, providing the required brake on buoyant household spending,&quot; said <Node id="2507"/>John Butler<Node id="2518"/> at <Node id="2522"/>HSBC<Node id="2526"/>.<Node id="2527"/>

<Node id="2529"/>So far there is little sign of the boom in the consumer and property markets easing. <Node id="2614"/>Land Registry<Node id="2627"/> figures <Node id="2636"/>yesterday<Node id="2645"/> confirmed the buoyancy of the property market, showing the average price of a house in <Node id="2733"/>England<Node id="2740"/> and <Node id="2745"/>Wales<Node id="2750"/> rose by nearly <Node id="2766"/>£7,000<Node id="2773"/> <Node id="2774"/>between April and June<Node id="2796"/>, from <Node id="2803"/>£110,570<Node id="2812"/> to <Node id="2816"/>£117,398<Node id="2825"/>.<Node id="2826"/>

<Node id="2828"/>The annual rate of growth is now running at <Node id="2872"/>10.83%<Node id="2878"/>, according to the registry, with the biggest rises in the <Node id="2937"/>Midlands<Node id="2945"/>. <Node id="2947"/>Greater London<Node id="2961"/> remains the most expensive place to buy a house - average prices rose <Node id="3032"/>6.65%<Node id="3037"/> to <Node id="3041"/>£205,831<Node id="3050"/> at the <Node id="3058"/>end of June<Node id="3069"/>, from <Node id="3076"/>£193,004<Node id="3085"/> a year earlier.<Node id="3101"/></TextWithNodes>
